St Michaels Way 13-5 miles.gpx_Alternative shorter ending
properties._desc: Through Marazion marshes. This route saves 2.5 miles, and makes the total distance of St Michael's Way 11 or 10.5 miles only (depending on the start). BUT...it requires crossing the A30 and the A394 - both busy and potentially dangerous roads without designated pedestrian crossing places. Also, there is a railway line to cross. And some cow fields. On the plus side, this alternate ending makes the route far more direct, and takes pilgrims through the wild beauty of Marazion marshes, an RSPB wetland and wildlife reserve. Also it avoids walking past the Longrock Industrial Estate, which is a blessing. But it misses Gulval Church, where Jesus himself is said to have walked - though the Church was obviously not there at the time. And it avoids the last slow approach to St Michael's Mount, when you see it coming from two miles away, and are at your most tired. This is a valuable moment on pilgriamge, the final striving when the end is in site but still so far away. Both routes are waymarked on the ground, so choose what suits you best. And always - ALWAYS - take care crossing roads. See this option on a GPX route here: https://goo.gl/GqSt0g

properties.name: St Michaels Way 13-5 miles.gpx_St Ives Start
properties._desc: Start from a more accessible centre - St Ives. This saves half a mile on the entire pilgrimage, making it a 13 mile or 10.5 mile walk - depending on which end you choose. We see the start as a choice of Saints - Ia or her brother Euny. Both have Churches and holy wells. But only Ia travelled here on a boat made from a leaf, because her brother Euny said she was too young to sail on the boat. Lelant was once the important centre, but now it is indisputably St Ives (named after Ia). The choice is yours. See both options on a GPX route here: https://goo.gl/GqSt0g
